<procstep>
<procdesc>Global Drought Hazard Frequency and Distribution used the Weighted Anomaly of Standardized Precipitation (WASP) developed by IRI, computed on a 2.5 minute grid from monthly average precipitation data for 1980 through 2000. The WASP assesses the precipitation deficit or surplus over a specified number of months, weighted by the magnitude of the seasonal cyclic variation in precipitation. A three-month running average was applied to the precipitation data and the median rainfall for the 21-year period calculated for each grid point. A mask was applied to eliminate grid points where the three-month running average precipitation was less than 1 millimeter per day. This excluded both desert regions and dry seasons from analysis. For the remaining points, a drought event was identified when the magnitude of a monthly precipitation deficit was less than or equal to 50 percent of its long-term median value for three or more consecutive months.

The final surface was created by classifiying the number of drought events into deciles, 10 classes of an approximately equal number of grid cells. An additional analysis mask excluded those portions of the land surface where the population density was less than 5 persons per square kilometer and there was no significant agriculture.</procdesc>
